questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: The arrow is pointing to the urethra.
questions.explanation: True. The image correctly identifies the urethra, the tube through which urine exits the body.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: The arrow is pointing to the vas deferens.
questions.explanation: True. The image correctly identifies the vas deferens, the duct that conveys sperm from the testicle to the urethra.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Females have a shorter urethra, therefore are at a reduced risk of contracting a UTI.
questions.explanation: False. Because females have a shorter urethra, they are at an increased risk of UTIs as bacteria have a shorter distance to travel to reach the bladder.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: If the bacterial infection of the urethra enters the kidney, it can enter the renal veins then possibly cause septic shock.
questions.explanation: True. A kidney infection (pyelonephritis) can become systemic if the bacteria enter the bloodstream through the renal veins, potentially leading to life-threatening septic shock.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Blood samples are never necessary for diagnosing a UTI.
questions.explanation: False. While a urine sample is the primary diagnostic tool, a blood sample may be taken if a more serious kidney infection or sepsis is suspected.
